    "content": "IFRS_9 | Components of a nominal amount | B6.3.16 There are two types of components of nominal amounts that can be designated as the hedged item in a hedging relationship: a component that is a proportion of an entire item or a layer component. The type of component changes the accounting outcome. An entity shall designate the component for accounting purposes consistently with its risk management objective.\n\nB6.3.17 An example of a component that is a proportion is 50 per cent of the contractual cash flows of a loan.\n\nB6.3.18 A layer component may be specified from a defined, but open, population, or from a defined nominal amount. Examples include: (a) part of a monetary transaction volume, for example, the next FC10 cash flows from sales denominated in a foreign currency after the first 201X;5 FC20 in March (b) a part of a physical volume, for example, the bottom layer, measuring 5 million cubic metres, of the natural gas stored in location XYZ; (c) a part of a physical or other transaction volume, for example, the first 100 barrels of the oil purchases in June 201X or the first 100 MWh of electricity sales in June 201X; or (d) a layer from the nominal amount of the hedged item, for example, the last CU80 million of a CU100 million firm commitment, the bottom layer of CU20 million of a CU100 million fixed-rate bond or the top layer of CU30 million from a total amount of CU100 million of fixed- rate debt that can be prepaid at fair value (the defined nominal amount is CU100 million)."
